privata . . . custodia] It appears that the acta of the Senatus, except the Senatus consulta, were kept by the consuls during their consulship, a practice that might have led to great abuses. Cicero speaks of this practice again in the oration Pro Archia, c. 5. It is difficult to suppose that a consul after the term of his office had expired, could have kept such records as the evidence of the conspiracy.
